docs.abstract: Some of the most consequential movements in American law and politics began amid defeat and panic.
docs.snippet: Some of the most consequential movements in American law and politics began amid defeat and panic.
docs.lead_paragraph: If we lived in normal political times, our new president would be enjoying his honeymoon period, those few blissful weeks of good will and high hopes that usually accompany the start of an administration. Instead, the election of Donald J. Trump to the nation’s highest office has provoked an opposition movement that is extraordinary in American history, with millions of people devoted to stopping whatever it is he might want to do.

headline.main: A ‘Resistance’ Stands Against Trump. But What Will It Stand For?

docs.abstract: Black dancers, musicians and artists have invigorated what had long been considered a whites-only space.
docs.snippet: Black dancers, musicians and artists have invigorated what had long been considered a whites-only space.
docs.lead_paragraph: RICHMOND, Va. — Janine Bell lived in Richmond for 35 years without visiting Monument Avenue. But that changed in July, when Ms. Bell threw a gathering honoring Emmett Till under the shadow of a statue of Robert E. Lee.

headline.main: In Richmond, Black Dance Claims a Space Near Robert E. Lee
headline.print_headline: Black Dance Finds a Powerful Backdrop

docs.abstract: The Supremes smack down a prehistoric president.
docs.snippet: The Supremes smack down a prehistoric president.
docs.lead_paragraph: There are leaders who are ahead of their times, leaders who are behind their times, and then there’s Donald Trump, who comes from another time altogether. He’s stuck somewhere closer to the Stone Age than to Stonewall. And the Supreme Court just told him so.

docs.abstract: A small contingent of country artists and industry players have been speaking up in a business that likes to shut down dissent.
docs.snippet: A small contingent of country artists and industry players have been speaking up in a business that likes to shut down dissent.
docs.lead_paragraph: Less than 30 minutes after TMZ posted a video of the country star Morgan Wallen using a racial slur on Feb. 2, Mickey Guyton, the only Black female country singer signed to a major label, tweeted her reaction: “The hate runs deep.”

headline.main: A New Generation Pushes Nashville to Address Racism in Its Ranks
headline.print_headline: Nashville Urged to Address Racism Within Its Ranks

docs.abstract: A story about protesters burning Bibles drew condemnation from conservatives. It now appears to have been wildly exaggerated — and the first viral hit in Russia’s 2020 disinformation campaign.
docs.snippet: A story about protesters burning Bibles drew condemnation from conservatives. It now appears to have been wildly exaggerated — and the first viral hit in Russia’s 2020 disinformation campaign.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For some of President Trump’s loudest cheerleaders, it was a story too good to check out: Black Lives Matters protesters in Portland, Ore., had burned a stack of Bibles, and then topped off the fire with American flags. There was even a video to prove it.

headline.main: A Bible Burning, a Russian News Agency and a Story Too Good to Check Out
headline.print_headline: Bible-Burning Video Goes Viral, A Win for Russia Disinformation

docs.abstract: Alabama is more than its shading on the electoral map.
docs.snippet: Alabama is more than its shading on the electoral map.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Deep South is not generally known for its labor agitation, which is why it might come as a surprise for some to learn that it is in Alabama where workers have mounted one of the largest and most aggressive efforts to unionize Amazon in recent memory.

headline.main: The Deep South Has a Rich History of Resistance, as Amazon Is Learning
headline.print_headline: Amazon and the South’s Union History

docs.abstract: The Young America’s Foundation, a well-funded group based in Washington, is on a mission to “restore sanity” at schools by deploying provocative speakers.
docs.snippet: The Young America’s Foundation, a well-funded group based in Washington, is on a mission to “restore sanity” at schools by deploying provocative speakers.
docs.lead_paragraph: BUFFALO — “Let’s give it up for the racists that are hosting this event!” someone yelled, and the crowd roared, foot-stomping in unison, then breaking into song: Woody Guthrie’s “This Land Is Your Land.” One member of the audience held up a sign, “Queers Against Islamaphobia.” Another unfurled a banner: “Muslims Welcome. Fascists Get Out.”

headline.main: The Conservative Force Behind Speeches Roiling College Campuses
headline.print_headline: Fiery Speeches on Campuses,  Backed by a Conservative Force

docs.abstract: A recent print ad in support of Christine Blasey Ford is part of a long history of advertisements in the paper whose main purpose is to forward a cause.
docs.snippet: A recent print ad in support of Christine Blasey Ford is part of a long history of advertisements in the paper whose main purpose is to forward a cause.
docs.lead_paragraph: You may have noticed a bold advertisement in The New York Times on Wednesday: a full page with the names of 1,600 men, in a tiny font, surrounding a box in the center stating: “We believe Anita Hill. We also believe Christine Blasey Ford.”

headline.main: Your Beliefs Here: A Look at Advocacy Advertising in The Times
